The Kepler-1348 Exoplanetary System


Overview

Kepler-1348 is a star with 1.04 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.04 times its radius. It is located 3958.95 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 3.72 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

Kepler-1348 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the Kepler-1348 system


Kepler-1348 b

Kepler-1348 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory, in 2016-05, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.18 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of Kepler-1348 b is 4.420 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-1348 b is 1.940 that of Earth. With a mass below 5 Earth masses, a density of 3.33, and a semi-major axis of 0.1834 astronomical units, Kepler-1348 b could, potentially, be an ocean world - a planet with no dry land.
